                                                          BEFORE JUMPING TO AWS 
#####################################################################################################################################################################

(1) DevOps Basics
--------------------

Q1. What is DevOps?
üëâ DevOps is a culture and set of practices that combine Development (Dev) and Operations (Ops) to deliver software faster, more reliably, and continuously.

Q2. Why do we need DevOps?
üëâ To bridge the gap between developers and operations, automate processes, and release software quickly with fewer bugs.

Q3. How is DevOps different from traditional software development?
üëâ Traditional: Separate Dev & Ops teams ‚Üí slow releases.
üëâ DevOps: Collaboration + automation ‚Üí faster, reliable releases.

Q4. Name some tools used in DevOps.
üëâ Git, Jenkins, Docker, Kubernetes, Terraform, Ansible, Prometheus, ELK Stack.


(2) Goals of DevOps
----------------------

Q1. What are the main goals of DevOps?
üëâ Faster delivery, automation, better collaboration, CI/CD, high quality software, and quick recovery from failures.

Q2. How does DevOps improve collaboration?
üëâ By breaking silos: Dev, QA, and Ops work together with shared tools and responsibilities.

Q3. How does DevOps ensure faster recovery from failures?
üëâ With CI/CD, automated rollback, monitoring, and backups.


(3) Key DevOps Practices
--------------------------

Q1. What is CI/CD?
üëâ Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment ‚Äì automates code integration, testing, and deployment.

Q2. What is Infrastructure as Code (IaC)?
üëâ Managing infrastructure (servers, networks, etc.) using code (e.g., Terraform, Ansible).

Q3. What is Automated Testing in DevOps?
üëâ Running tests automatically to detect bugs early.

Q4. Why is monitoring and logging important in DevOps?
üëâ To track performance, detect issues quickly, and troubleshoot failures.

Q5. What is containerization?
üëâ Packaging apps in containers (e.g., Docker, Kubernetes) so they run anywhere.

Q6. What is the difference between Continuous Integration, Continuous Delivery, and Continuous Deployment?
üëâ CI: Merge code frequently + test automatically.
üëâ CD (Delivery): Automated release pipeline but manual approval before deploy.
üëâ CD (Deployment): Fully automated deployment without manual approval.

Q7. What is the role of Terraform in DevOps?
üëâ IaC tool to provision infrastructure (servers, networks, databases) in a repeatable way.

Q8. How is Kubernetes different from Docker?
üëâ Docker = containerization.
üëâ Kubernetes = orchestration of multiple containers.

Q9. Why do we need monitoring in DevOps? Give examples of tools.
üëâ To detect performance issues & failures quickly. Tools: Prometheus, Grafana, ELK, CloudWatch.


(4) IT Infrastructure Basics :
-------------------------------

Q1. What is IT Infrastructure?
üëâ The basic physical and virtual resources (servers, storage, network, security, etc.) required to run IT services and software.

Q2. Difference between physical and virtual infrastructure?
üëâ Physical: Actual servers/hardware.
üëâ Virtual: Created using virtualization/cloud (VMs, containers).

Q3. Why is IT infrastructure considered the backbone of IT services?
üëâ Because without servers, network, storage, and security, no application can run or be delivered.


(5) Components of IT Infrastructure :
--------------------------------------

Q1. What are the key components of IT infrastructure?
üëâ Servers, network, power supply, storage, backup, and security systems.

Q2. Why is backup important in IT infrastructure?
üëâ To protect data from failures, cyberattacks, or accidental loss.

Q3. What is the difference between storage and backup?
üëâ Storage = where live data resides.
üëâ Backup = copies of data for recovery in case of failure/loss.

Q4. How is security handled in IT infrastructure?
üëâ Using firewalls, antivirus, encryption, access control, and monitoring.



(6) On-Premises Infrastructure :
---------------------------------

Q1. What is On-Prem Infrastructure?
üëâ All IT resources (servers, storage, network) are owned and managed at your office/data center.

Q2. Who is responsible for maintenance in On-Prem?
üëâ The organization itself (buying hardware, hiring IT staff, managing security).

Q3. When would a company prefer On-Prem over Cloud?
üëâ When strict security/compliance is needed, or legacy applications can‚Äôt run on cloud.

Q4. What skills do IT staff need for managing On-Prem infrastructure?
üëâ Server administration, networking, backup, troubleshooting, hardware maintenance.


(7) Challenges of On-Prem  :
-----------------------------

Q1. What are the main challenges of On-Prem infrastructure?
üëâ High cost, need more manpower, scalability is hard, downtime risk, network issues, and security responsibility.

Q2. Why is scalability a challenge in On-Prem?
üëâ Because adding resources (servers, storage) requires buying new hardware ‚Üí takes time & money.

Q3. How does downtime affect business in On-Prem?
üëâ Leads to loss of revenue, poor customer experience, and reduced productivity.



(8) Cloud Computing :
------------------------

Q1. What is Cloud Computing?
üëâ Delivery of IT resources (servers, storage, databases, software) over the internet on a pay-as-you-go basis.

Q2. What are the benefits of cloud computing?
üëâ Low cost, pay as you go, scalability, high availability, built-in security, and automated backup & recovery.

Q3. Name some popular cloud providers.
üëâ AWS, Azure, GCP, Salesforce, Alibaba Cloud, DigitalOcean.

Q4. What are the service models of cloud computing?
üëâ IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service), PaaS (Platform as a Service), SaaS (Software as a Service).

Q5. Explain IaaS, PaaS, SaaS with examples.?
üëâ IaaS: AWS EC2, Azure VM (infrastructure only).
üëâ PaaS: Google App Engine, AWS Elastic Beanstalk (deploy apps without managing infra).
üëâ SaaS: Gmail, Salesforce, Office 365 (ready-to-use software).

Q6. What are deployment models of cloud?
üëâ Public Cloud, Private Cloud, Hybrid Cloud, Multi-Cloud.

Q7. How does ‚Äúpay-as-you-go‚Äù reduce IT cost?
üëâ You pay only for used resources (compute, storage, network) ‚Üí no upfront investment.


(9) On-Prem vs Cloud :
----------------------

Q1. What is the main difference between On-Prem and Cloud?
üëâ On-Prem = you own & maintain hardware, Cloud = provider maintains it.

Q2. Which one is more scalable: On-Prem or Cloud?
üëâ Cloud.

Q3. Which one requires more staff: On-Prem or Cloud?
üëâ On-Prem.

Q4. Why is cloud more reliable than On-Prem?
üëâ Cloud providers offer redundancy, failover, backups, and SLA-based uptime.

Q5. Can a company use both On-Prem and Cloud? What is it called?
üëâ Yes, it‚Äôs called Hybrid Cloud.



(10) Cloud Service Models :
----------------------------

Q1. What are the three main cloud service models?
üëâ IaaS, PaaS, SaaS.

Q2. What is the difference between IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS in one line?
üëâ IaaS = infrastructure, PaaS = platform, SaaS = ready-to-use software.

Q3. Who is responsible for managing infrastructure in SaaS?
üëâ The cloud provider.


(11) IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) :
------------------------------------------

Q1. What is IaaS?
üëâ Cloud provider gives raw infrastructure (VMs, storage, networking) and you build everything on top of it.

Q2. Give an example scenario of using IaaS.
üëâ Hosting a Java web app on AWS EC2 ‚Üí install OS, runtime, Tomcat, MySQL, and deploy the app.

Q3. What responsibilities does the customer have in IaaS?
üëâ Install OS, runtimes, web servers, deploy apps, manage patches & security.

Q4. Name some common IaaS providers.
üëâ AWS EC2, Azure Virtual Machines, Google Compute Engine, Oracle Cloud, DigitalOcean Droplets.

Q5. What is the advantage of IaaS?
üëâ High flexibility & control because you configure everything yourself.



(12) PaaS (Platform as a Service) :
------------------------------------

Q1. What is PaaS?
üëâ Cloud provider gives a ready-made platform (OS, runtime, web server), you just deploy your app.

Q2. What is the main difference between IaaS and PaaS?
üëâ In IaaS you manage OS + runtime + app, in PaaS you only manage the app.

Q3. Give an example scenario of using PaaS.
üëâ Deploy a Spring Boot app on Heroku or Google App Engine ‚Üí push code, provider manages environment & scaling.

Q4. What responsibilities does the customer have in PaaS?
üëâ Only write & deploy code, manage data.

Q5. Name some PaaS providers.
üëâ Heroku, Google App Engine, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure App Service.

Q6. What is the benefit of PaaS?
üëâ Faster development and deployment since you don‚Äôt manage infrastructure.



(13) SaaS (Software as a Service) :
--------------------------------------

Q1. What is SaaS?
üëâ Ready-to-use software delivered over the internet, no installation or setup required.

Q2. What is the customer‚Äôs responsibility in SaaS?
üëâ Just log in and use the software.

Q3. Give examples of SaaS applications.
üëâ Zoom, Google Docs, Dropbox, Microsoft 365, Jira, Salesforce.

Q4. What is the biggest advantage of SaaS?
üëâ Zero maintenance ‚Üí provider handles updates, backups, security.

Q5. How do IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS differ in terms of control?
üëâ IaaS = max control, SaaS = least control, PaaS = in between.

Q6. Which model is best for developers who want to only focus on coding?
üëâ PaaS.

Q7. Which model would you choose for running Gmail or Salesforce?
üëâ SaaS.

Q8. Which model would you choose for hosting your own customized ERP system?
üëâ IaaS (because you need full control).

Q9. Which cloud model supports ‚Äúlift and shift‚Äù migration from on-prem to cloud?
üëâ IaaS (easy to move VMs and apps as-is).

Q10. Why is SaaS considered cost-effective for small businesses?
üëâ No upfront infra cost, subscription-based pricing.


                                                           JUMPING TO AWS 
#####################################################################################################################################################################

(1) ‚úÖ AWS Cloud :
---------------------

Q1. What is AWS?
A. AWS (Amazon Web Services) is the most popular cloud provider offering 200+ services.

Q2. When was AWS launched?
A. In 2006.

Q3. How many countries use AWS?
A. More than 190+ countries.

Q4. What pricing model does AWS use?
A. Pay-as-you-go (only pay for what you use).

Q5. Why is AWS the market leader in cloud?
A. Because of its global infra, large service catalog, security, scalability, and continuous innovation.

Q6. Difference between Free Tier and Pay-as-you-go?
A. Free Tier ‚Üí Limited usage free for 12 months.
Pay-as-you-go ‚Üí Pay only for consumed resources.

Q7. Why companies prefer AWS over on-prem?
A. Scalability, lower upfront cost, faster deployment, high availability.


(2) ‚úÖ Region & Availability Zone :
-----------------------------------------

Q1. What is a Region in AWS?
A. A geographical area like Mumbai (ap-south-1) or Virginia (us-east-1).

Q2. What is an Availability Zone (AZ)?
A. An isolated data center within a Region with separate power and networking.

Q3. How many Regions and AZs does AWS have?
A. 33 Regions and 105 AZs (growing).

Q4. Why are AZs important?
A. They provide high availability and fault tolerance.

Q5. What if you deploy in a single AZ?
A. App faces downtime if that AZ fails.

Q6. Can resources be accessed across Regions?
A. Yes, but with higher latency and extra cost.


(3) üåç Why Global Setup Matters :
------------------------------------

Q1. Why does AWS have Regions worldwide?
A. To reduce latency and serve users closer to their location.

Q2. What‚Äôs the benefit of multiple Regions?
A. Compliance, redundancy, and disaster recovery.

Q3. Example where Region choice is critical?
A. Banking apps must keep data in-country due to compliance laws.

Q4. Example: who secures S3 storage infra?
A. AWS manages infra, but customer sets permissions (IAM policies).



(4) üñ•Ô∏è AWS  Services :
----------------------------------

Q1. Can you name some of the core AWS services you have worked with or know about?

AWS offers 200+ services, here are some of the most popular and important ones, grouped by purpose:

üñ•Ô∏è 1. Compute Services
**************************
Service							Description
EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)			Create virtual machines (hourly billing)
Elastic Beanstalk				PaaS for managing full web applications (auto-scaling, deployment, etc.)
Lambda	Serverless computing ‚Äî 			just upload code, no servers needed
ECS (Elastic Container Service)			Run and manage Docker containers
EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service)		Run Kubernetes clusters on AWS

üì¶ 2. Storage Services
**************************
Service							Description
S3 (Simple Storage Service)			Object storage for unlimited files (like Google Drive but for apps)
EFS (Elastic File System)			Shared file system ‚Äî mountable to multiple EC2s like a network drive

üóÑÔ∏è 3. Database Services
**************************
Service							Description
RDS (Relational Database Service)		Managed SQL databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.)
DynamoDB					NoSQL managed database (not in your original list, but widely used)

üîí 4. Security & Access
**************************
Service							Description
IAM (Identity & Access Management)		Manage users, roles, and permissions for AWS resources

üåê 5. Networking
**************************
Service							Description
VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)			Create a private network within AWS
Route 53					Domain Name System (DNS) service for domain mapping
üîî 6. Monitoring & Notifications
Service							Description
CloudWatch					Monitor resources, log events, set alarms
SNS (Simple Notification Service)		Send email, SMS, push notifications automatically


NOTE : 
Short way to say it :=  AWS (cloud provider) ‚Üí EC2 (AWS Service) ‚Üí EBS (Component of EC2) ‚Üí Volumes, Snapshots, Lifecycle Manager (Sub-components of EBS)


(4.1) ‚úÖ AWS EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) :
---------------------------------------------
Definition:
Amazon EC2 is a web service that provides secure, resizable compute capacity (virtual servers) in the cloud. 
It allows you to run applications on virtual machines called instances.

** INSTANCES **

Q1. What is Amazon EC2?
üëâ EC2 is Amazon‚Äôs service to create and run virtual servers (instances) in the cloud.

Q2. What is an EC2 instance?
üëâ An EC2 instance is a virtual machine running on Amazon‚Äôs cloud infrastructure.

Q3. What is the benefit of EC2?
üëâ Scalability, pay-as-you-go pricing, flexibility of choosing OS, storage, and instance type.

Q4. How do you access an EC2 instance?
üëâ Using SSH (for Linux) or RDP (for Windows) along with a key pair.

Q5. What are EC2 instance types?
üëâ General purpose, Compute optimized, Memory optimized, Storage optimized, Accelerated computing.

Q6. How does EC2 pricing work?
üëâ Pricing models: On-Demand, Reserved Instances, Spot Instances, and Savings Plans.

Q7. What happens when an EC2 instance is stopped vs terminated?
üëâ Stopped ‚Üí Data in EBS is retained. Terminated ‚Üí Data in instance store is lost.

Q8. Difference between vertical scaling and horizontal scaling in EC2?
üëâ Vertical: Increase instance size (more CPU/RAM).
üëâ Horizontal: Add more instances behind a load balancer.

Q9. How does Elastic IP work in EC2?
üëâ It‚Äôs a static public IPv4 that you can remap to any instance.

Q10. What security features does EC2 provide?
üëâ Security Groups, NACLs, Key Pairs, IAM Roles.


                   ** Amazon Machine Images **

Definition:
An AMI is a template that contains the software configuration (OS, application server, applications) required to launch an EC2 instance.

Q1. What is an AMI?
üëâ A pre-configured image to create EC2 instances.

Q2. What are the types of AMIs?
üëâ Public AMIs, Private AMIs, AWS Marketplace AMIs.

Q3. What does an AMI contain?
üëâ OS, Application Server, Applications, and launch permissions.

Q4. How do you create a custom AMI?
üëâ Stop the instance ‚Üí Create Image ‚Üí Use the AMI for new instances.

Q5. Difference between AMI and Snapshot?
üëâ AMI = Full system image (OS + Apps + Data).
üëâ Snapshot = Backup of EBS volume.


                   ** Elastic Block Store **

Definition:
Amazon EBS provides block-level storage volumes for EC2 instances. Volumes behave like raw, unformatted hard drives that can be attached to instances.

(a) Volumes
------------
Persistent block storage attached to EC2.

Q1. What is an EBS Volume?
üëâ A virtual hard drive for EC2 instances.

Q2. What are EBS volume types?
üëâ General Purpose SSD (gp3/gp2), Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1/io2), Throughput Optimized HDD (st1), Cold HDD (sc1).

Q3. Can EBS volumes be attached to multiple instances?
üëâ Normally no, but with EBS Multi-Attach (for io1/io2 volumes) it‚Äôs possible.

(b) Snapshots
------------------
Point-in-time backups of EBS volumes.

Q4. What is an EBS Snapshot?
üëâ Incremental backup of an EBS volume stored in S3.

Q5. Difference between Snapshot and AMI?
üëâ Snapshot is volume backup. AMI is full machine image.

(c) Lifecycle Manager
------------------------
Automates the creation, retention, and deletion of snapshots.

Q6. What is EBS Lifecycle Manager?
üëâ It automates EBS snapshot management.

Q7. Why do we use Lifecycle Manager?
üëâ To schedule daily/weekly backups and retain them as per policy.

Q8. What is the difference between EBS and Instance Store?
üëâ EBS is persistent storage, Instance Store is temporary storage tied to instance lifecycle.

Q9. What is the durability of EBS?
üëâ 99.999% availability within an AZ.


                   ** Security Groups **

Definition:
Security Group is a virtual firewall that controls inbound and outbound traffic for EC2 instances.

Q1. What is a Security Group in AWS?
üëâ A firewall that allows or denies traffic to EC2 instances.

Q2. What type of rules does a Security Group support?
üëâ Inbound (incoming traffic) and Outbound (outgoing traffic).

Q3. Are Security Groups stateful or stateless?
üëâ Stateful ‚Üí if inbound traffic is allowed, the response is automatically allowed.

Q4. Difference between Security Groups and NACLs?
üëâ Security Groups = Instance level, Stateful.
üëâ NACLs = Subnet level, Stateless.

Q5. How many Security Groups can be attached to one EC2 instance?
üëâ By default, 5 per instance (limit can be increased).

Q6. What happens if no rule is added in a Security Group?
üëâ All inbound traffic is denied, but all outbound is allowed.


                   ** Key Pairs **
Definition:
Key Pairs are a set of public and private keys used to securely connect to an EC2 instance (SSH for Linux, RDP for Windows).

Q1. What is a Key Pair in EC2?
üëâ A public-private key mechanism to authenticate access to an instance.

Q2. Which file format is used for Key Pairs?
üëâ .pem (Linux SSH) and .ppk (Windows PuTTY).

Q3. What happens if you lose your Key Pair?
üëâ You can‚Äôt connect directly. You must create a new key, stop the instance, detach the root volume, attach it to another instance, add the new key to authorized_keys, and then reattach.

Q4. Can we share Key Pairs across regions?
üëâ No, Key Pairs are region-specific.


                   ** Elastic IPs **
Definition:
Elastic IP is a static IPv4 address that you can assign to any instance in a region.

Q1. What is an Elastic IP?
üëâ A static, public IPv4 address that remains fixed even if the instance stops/restarts.

Q2. How is Elastic IP different from normal Public IP?
üëâ Public IP changes when an instance is stopped and started, while Elastic IP stays the same.

Q3. How many Elastic IPs can an AWS account have?
üëâ By default, 5 per region (can request increase).

Q4. Is Elastic IP free?
üëâ Free only if it‚Äôs associated with a running instance. If not used, AWS charges for it.


                   ** Elastic Load Balancing **
Definition:
Elastic Load Balancer automatically distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances.
Sub-components of ELB like,
- Application Load Balancer (ALB) ‚Äì Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS)
- Network Load Balancer (NLB) ‚Äì Layer 4 (TCP/UDP)
- Gateway Load Balancer (GWLB) ‚Äì For security appliances

Q1. What is Elastic Load Balancing?
üëâ A service to automatically balance traffic between multiple instances.

Q2. What are the types of Load Balancers in AWS?
üëâ ALB, NLB, GWLB.

Q3. What is a Target Group in Load Balancing?
üëâ A group of EC2 instances or services that receive traffic from the load balancer.

Q4. Difference between ALB and NLB?
üëâ ALB works at HTTP/HTTPS level (Layer 7), NLB works at TCP/UDP (Layer 4).

Q5. What health check mechanism does ELB use?
üëâ Periodically checks if targets (instances) are healthy before sending traffic.

Q6. Can we attach an ELB to instances in different Availability Zones?
üëâ Yes, ELB supports multi-AZ deployments.


                   ** Elastic Load Balancing **
Definition:
Auto Scaling automatically increases or decreases the number of EC2 instances based on demand.

Q1. What is Auto Scaling in AWS?
üëâ A feature that automatically adjusts the number of EC2 instances based on traffic demand.

Q2. What are the components of Auto Scaling?
üëâ Launch Configuration/Launch Template, Auto Scaling Group, Scaling Policies.

Q3. Why do we use Auto Scaling?
üëâ To handle sudden traffic spikes and reduce costs when traffic is low.

Q4. Difference between Dynamic Scaling and Scheduled Scaling?
üëâ Dynamic = Based on real-time demand (e.g., CPU > 80%).
üëâ Scheduled = Based on fixed schedule (e.g., every day at 9 AM).

Q5. What is a Cooldown period in Auto Scaling?
üëâ A waiting period to prevent multiple scaling actions in quick succession.

Q6. Can Auto Scaling work with Load Balancers?
üëâ Yes, Auto Scaling integrates with ELB to distribute traffic automatically.






(4) üóÑÔ∏è AWS Storage Types : 
--------------------------------

Q1. What storage options does AWS provide?
A. Object Storage (images, videos, backups), Block Storage used for DBs, OS, transactional apps), File Storage (Shared file systems, enterprise apps).

Q2. Example of Object Storage?
A. Amazon S3.

Q3. Example of Block Storage?
A. Amazon EBS.

Q4. Example of File Storage?
A. Amazon EFS.

Q5. Difference between S3 and EBS?
A. S3 = object storage (unlimited, global).
EBS = block storage for EC2 (attached like a disk).

Q6. When use EFS?
A. For multiple EC2s needing shared file system.

Q7. Which storage is best for backups?
A. S3 (cheap, scalable, durable).






(6) üåê AWS Networking :
----------------------------

Q1. What is VPC?
A. Virtual Private Cloud ‚Üí isolated private network in AWS.

Q2. What is an Internet Gateway?
A. Connects VPC to the internet.

Q3. What is Route 53?
A. AWS DNS service.

Q4. Why use VPC?
A. To secure apps with private networking.

Q5. Difference between Public and Private Subnet?
A. Public ‚Üí has internet access, Private ‚Üí no internet access.

Q6. Why use Route 53?
A. For domain registration, DNS routing, and health checks.


(7) üîê AWS Security :
---------------------------

Q1. What is IAM?
A. Identity and Access Management service in AWS.

Q2. What is MFA?
A. Multi-Factor Authentication (extra layer of login security).

Q3. Example of IAM entity?
A. Users, Groups, Roles.

Q4. Best practices for IAM?
A. Least privilege access, enable MFA, rotate keys.

Q5. Difference between IAM Role and IAM User?
A. User = human identity.
Role = temporary access for services/apps.

Q6. Why use Security Groups?
A. To control inbound/outbound traffic to EC2.


(8) üìä AWS Monitoring :
---------------------------

Q1. What is CloudWatch?
A. AWS monitoring service for logs, metrics, alerts.

Q2. What is CloudTrail?
A. Tracks API calls and activities in AWS.

Q3. Why is monitoring needed?
A. To detect issues early and maintain performance.

Q4. Difference between CloudWatch and CloudTrail?
A. CloudWatch ‚Üí performance monitoring.
CloudTrail ‚Üí auditing and security tracking.

Q5. How do alarms in CloudWatch help?
A. Alert when thresholds are crossed (e.g., CPU > 80%).

Q6. Why is monitoring critical in production?
A. Ensures uptime, helps in troubleshooting and scaling.


(9) üõ†Ô∏è AWS Database Services :
---------------------------------

Q1. What is RDS?
A. Relational Database Service ‚Üí managed DB (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.).

Q2. What is DynamoDB?
A. NoSQL database.

Q3. What is Aurora?
A. High-performance MySQL/PostgreSQL compatible DB.

Q4. RDS vs DynamoDB difference?
A. RDS ‚Üí relational (SQL), DynamoDB ‚Üí NoSQL (key-value).

Q5. Why use Aurora over MySQL?
A. 5x faster, highly scalable, fully managed.

Q6. When to choose DynamoDB?
A. For high-speed apps with unstructured data.









